Certainly! Below is a simple HTML file that allows you to control random emoji directions using the specified keys. The emojis will move in the direction corresponding to the keys you press. You can copy and paste this code into an HTML file and open it in a web browser to see it in action.

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Emoji Direction Control</title>
    <style>
        body {
            display: flex;
            justify-content: center;
            align-items: center;
            height: 100vh;
            background-color: #f0f0f0;
            font-size: 2rem;
            overflow: hidden;
        }
        #emoji {
            position: absolute;
            transition: transform 0.1s;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <div id="emoji">ðŸ˜€</div>
    <script>
        const emojiElement = document.getElementById('emoji');
        const step = 20; // Number of pixels to move

        // Initial position
        let x = window.innerWidth / 2;
        let y = window.innerHeight / 2;
        emojiElement.style.transform = `translate(${x}px, ${y}px)`;

        document.addEventListener('keydown', (event) => {
            switch (event.key) {
                case 'y': // Up left
                    x -= step;
                    y -= step;
                    break;
                case 'u': // Up right
                    x += step;
                    y -= step;
                    break;
                case 'g': // Left
                    x -= step;
                    break;
                case 'h': // Pass (do nothing)
                    break;
                case 'j': // Right
                    x += step;
                    break;
                case 'b': // Down left
                    x -= step;
                    y += step;
                    break;
                case 'n': // Down right
                    x += step;
                    y += step;
                    break;
                default:
                    return; // Exit this handler for other keys
            }
            // Update the emoji position
            emojiElement.style.transform = `translate(${x}px, ${y}px)`;
        });
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

### Instructions:
1. Copy the code above.
2. Paste it into a text editor and save it with a `.html` extension (e.g., `emoji_control.html`).
3. Open the saved file in a web browser.
4. Use the keys 'y', 'u', 'g', 'h', 'j', 'b', and 'n' to control the emoji's movement on the screen. 

Enjoy moving your emoji around!
